gration Metropolises -- t12. “A Fantasy in Fashion”: Luxury Dressing and African American Lifestyle Magazines in the 1980s -- t13. Racial Discrimination in Retail Settings: A Liberation Psychology Perspective -- t14. Does the Retail Environment Affect Mental Health? Satisfaction with Neighborhood Retail and Social Well-Being among African Americans in New York City -- tNOTES ON CONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRace has long shaped shopping experiences for many Americans. Retail exchanges and establishments have made headlines as flashpoints for conflict not only between blacks and whites, but also between whites, Mexicans, Asian Americans, and a wide variety of other ethnic groups, who have at times found themselves unwelcome at white-owned businesses. Race and Retail documents the extent to which retail establishments, both past and present, have often catered to specific ethnic and racial groups. Using an interdisciplinary approach, the original essays collected here explore selling and buying practices of nonwhite populations around the world and the barriers that shape these habits, such as racial discrimination, food deserts, and gentrification. The contributors highlight more contemporary issues by raising questions about how race informs business owners’ ideas about consumer demand, resulting in substandard quality and higher prices for minorities than in predominantly white neighborhoods. In a wide-ranging exploration of the subject, they also address revitalization and gentrification in South Korean and Latino neighborhoods in California, Arab and Turkish coffeehouses and hookah lounges in South Paterson, New Jersey, and tourist capoeira consumption in Brazil. Race and Retail illuminates the complex play of forces at work in racialized retail markets and the everyday impact of those forces on minority consumers. The essays demonstrate how past practice remains in force in subtle and not-so-subtle ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aConsumption (Economics)xSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMinoritieszUnited StatesxEconomic conditions. 0aRetail tradexSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aShoppingxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aStores, RetailxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBay, Mia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBay, Mia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBay, Mia.1 aBayouth, Neiset, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBayouth, Neiset.1 aCadava, Geraldo L ., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCadava, Geraldo L.1 aCarter-David, Siobhan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarter-David, Siobhan.1 aCooper, Melissa L ., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Melissa L.1 aEvett, Sophia R.1 aEvett, Sophia R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFabian, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFabian, Ann, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFabian, Ann.1 aGonzález, Erualdo R ., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzález, Erualdo R.1 aHakstian, Anne-Marie G.1 aHakstian, Anne-Marie G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeaton, John W.1 aHeaton, John W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenderson, Geraldine Rosa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenderson, Geraldine Rosa.1 aKenny, Bridget, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb